args: Several years after Harle\nwas sent to another world...
(I've learned quite a bit about my place\nof exile, but I've yet to find a way home.)
That man doesn't understand a THING!
My, my. What's gotten you so worked up?
Oh. You. *sigh* I'm simply fed up\nwith King Leonidas's naïveté.
That's certainly not a word I'd use\nto describe His Majesty. ＂Strict＂ or\n＂unrelenting,＂ maybe. What happened?
You know about how this world is facing\ndesertification, yes?
I do. It would seem the grave consequence\nof eradicating those dragons is happening\nquicker than expected. We can't keep up.
I hear that even the old capital, Sol\nAlberia, has been swallowed by sand.
('Twas disorder they sowed,\nand now they reap.)
We're migrating those who lost their\nhomes to safer places—like Valkaheim.
The problem is, we're running low on\nresources. We simply can't afford to\nwaste them on the weak.
Thus, I suggested we should instead trim\nthe fat. Get rid of those devoid of use.\nI've even drafted a plan for it here.
＂On Saving the Nation.＂ Hm...\nI can certainly see the efficiency in it all.\nWhat did King Leonidas have to say?
That we will not change course. And he\nwouldn't hear anything to the contrary.
A country cannot grow if we prune the\nbuds of talent before they even develop.

The weak will die out whether we have a
hand in their culling or not. Yet we must
also wait for those who would one day
become stronger.
The grace he would grant is nothing but\na waste of precious time and resources.
A rather hasty judgment, don't you think?

Not at all. I've had plenty of time to mull
it over. No matter how long we wait, we'll
never find a leader more exceptional or
talented than myself.
The time is ripe. We need to enact our\nplan to assassinate the king. I will rule\nin his stead.
You really wish to take on such\na bothersome role?
If a ruler outlives his use, I have no choice\nbut to seize his power for myself. The hour\nfor revolution is nigh.

Heh... I can only imagine the look on
his face when his authority is stripped
away by a man who crawled up the
ranks from base servitude!
Hm. I could have sworn I heard\nsomeone else in here.
Your ears play tricks, fair madam.\nNow, your report, if you will.
With that, I must take my leave. Should\nyou find anything amiss, do contact me.
I will. Your help is always appreciated.
That was Cassandra, the court sorceress.\nWas she not in your world?
I know her name, but I have never met\nher personally.
She was retired, but the former king's will\ndecreed that she support King Leonidas.

I have asked her to do some research into
other worlds. In particular, to see if it's
possible to voluntarily open a gate into
one of them.

To trim the fat, remember? It'd be too
much trouble to kill the weak, so I thought
we could instead round them up and dump
them into another world.
That was quicker than I expected.\nDid you forget something?
It is a pleasure to meet you, Lady\nCassandra. I have come seeking\nyour wisdom. My name is Harle.
Is this some sort of jest?\nWe JUST saw each other earlier today.
You did in fact meet with the Harle of\nthis world. However, this would be your\nfirst time meeting me.
I see... So essentially, you're a foreign\nbody that was shoved into this world by\nsomeone else.
For the time being. Now,\nwhat is it you want from me?
It's quite a simple request. I would like\nto work together to find a way back to\nthe world whence I came.
Sorry, but no. Your situation is pitiable,\nbut I've far too much on my plate as well.
I'd not dream of assuming otherwise.\nIndeed, no matter how much you do\nbelieve me, I've spun quite the yarn.
You wouldn't have time to focus on\nsomething so far-fetched. I certainly\nunderstand that. However...
What if I were to offer myself as a test\nsubject?

From what I can tell, you have an
impressive collection of books on
communing with the dead and
bringing them back to life in here.
I'd wager you have your own reasons for\nagreeing to perform the other Harle's\nresearch.
And what better research subject than a\nman from another world? Tempting, no?
From then on, I helped Cassandra with her\nresearch, and in turn was able to investigate\nmeans of getting back home.
But one day, we suddenly lost contact.\nI didn't hear from her for several months.
What happened? The way I lost touch with\nyou so suddenly, I'd thought you'd died.\n
My apologies. There was something I\nneeded to test.
You understand what a chain of causality\nis, right?

It's the force that tethers a person to their
world, no? So that even if you manage to
travel through time, you'll quickly be
pulled back to where you came from.

Correct. And a different time is the same
thing as a different world. Normally, it
would be impossible for someone to exist
in another world for as long as you have.
Not that one would expect otherwise.\nFor two of the same person cannot exist in\nthe same world.
Worlds themselves are quite delicate,\nyou see. They'll try to correct paradoxes\nand remove any sorts of foreign bodies.
And yet, I have been able to remain\nhere for some time now.

That's right. According to my research, the
only way that's possible is to either use
the Dawnshard or to be severed from the
chain of causality.
And yet, as I told you,  I have nothing of\nthe sort in my possession.
Which leaves us with only one option.
Though even if that's the case, there\nshould be a limit to how long you're\nable to stay in another world.
I wasn't getting anywhere without\nlooking into that. So I performed a\nlittle experiment.
To see if your chain of causality\nreally had been severed.
Those affected by this phenomenon\ncannot remain in people's memories.
After a few months without contact,\nno trace of you would remain in the\nmind of another.
Thus did I purposely keep some distance\nfrom you. However, no matter how long I\nwas away, I could still remember you.
So does that mean...my chain of causality\nWASN'T severed?
It's the only theory that holds water.\nIt also helps me understand why you've\nbeen able to stay here for so long.
It means that your chain of causality\nis yet bound to your original world.
I wish I knew for certain. Do you know of\nanyone who could wield influence over\nsuch a thing?
...Yes, now that I think about it.
Well, then I hate to say it, but you're going\nto have to do something about them, or\nelse you're stuck here forever.

If I can't interfere with my chain of
causality myself, then perhaps I should
simply have myself removed from this
world.
Unfortunately, this is where our\ncollaborative efforts come to an end.
Hold it! While that method may indeed\nforce the world to right itself...

If something goes awry, not only will you
be unable to return whence you came,
but you might simply cease to exist!
Are you sure about this?
...Our partnership has been fruitful indeed,\nmy lady. I pray that your wish shall one\nday come true.
Now, let us begin.\nThe climax of this story is upon us.
